Introduction¶

Medical appointments arrangement is an important adminstrative process to ensure proper time management for both doctors and patients. When a patient makes an appointment, receives all the instruction needed. However, number of patients do not show up. So, what are the reasons behind this problem?

This project will investigate several factors/characteristics that may affect the show-up and no-show decisions to the appointment by analysing 'noshowappointments-kagglev2-may-2016.csv' document that collects data of 110,527 medical appointments in Brazil. Each appointment includes information for 14 associated variables/characteristics, which are:

  • PatientId: serial ID for a patient
  • AppointmentID: serial ID for an appointment
  • Gender: Gender of a patient (female coded as (F) or male coded as (M))
  • ScheduledDay: The day when a patient set up an appointment
  • AppointmentDay: The day of patient's appointment
  • Age: Age of the patient
  • Neighbourhood: the location of the hospital
  • Scholarship: tells us if a patient is enrolled in Brazilian welfare program, Bolsa Família (1 for enrolled, 0 for not)
  • Hypertension and Diabetes: tell us if a patient has the health issue or not(1 for infected, 0 for not)
  • Alcoholism: tell us if a patient consume alcohol or not(1 for consume, 0 for not)
  • Handicap: tell us the numbers of handicaps a patient would face
  • SMS_Received: tells us if the patient received an SMS (1 for recieved, 0 for not)
  • No_Show: whether the patient show-up or not (Yes for no-show, No for show-up)

This program is structured to answer the broad question mentioned above, so, we need to break it down into the following:

    1. What is the overall appointments' attendance performance of the patients?
    1. How the following factors are important in order to predict if a patient will show up for their scheduled appointment?
    • 2.1 Gender
    • 2.2 Age
    • 2.3 Neighbourhood
    • 2.4 Scholarship and SMS_Received
    • 2.5 Health issues (Hypertension, Diabetes and Alcoholism)
    1. How is the time difference between the scheduled day and appointment day affect patient's decision?

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Data are now trimmed and cleaned, so we are ready for exploration. In this section, we are answering the questions mentioned in the introduction.

Research Question 1 (What is the overall appointments' attendance performance of the patients?)¶

1-1 No_Show Summary Table¶

Note:

  • The patient showed up for the appointment if 'No_Show' = 'No'.
  • The patient missed the appointment if 'No_Show' = 'Yes'
In [57]:
# No_Show distribution
df_No_ShowYes = df[df['No_Show'] == 'Yes'] #missed
df_No_ShowNo = df[df['No_Show'] == 'No']   #showed

Yes = len(df_No_ShowYes)
No = len(df_No_ShowNo)
Total = Yes + No

# No_Show summary table
No_Show_dic = { 'Count':[Yes, No, Total], 'Percentage (%)':[Yes*100/Total, No*100/Total, Yes*100/Total + No*100/Total]}
No_Show_table = pd.DataFrame(No_Show_dic)
index0 = ['Missed', 'Showed', 'Total']
No_Show_table.index = index0

#show the table
No_Show_table

1-2 No_Show Summary Graph¶

In [58]:
def bar_plot(arg1, arg2):
    #No-Show bar graph
    arg1.iloc[:2,:1].plot(kind='bar', color='Green');
    plt.xlabel('No_Show')
    plt.ylabel('Patients Count')
    plt.title(f'{arg2.title()} Distribution');
    plt.legend();

bar_plot(No_Show_table, "No Show")

The No Show table and bar graph indicates that the number of showed up appointments is almost 60% greater than the number of missed appointments.

Like the order of cases in the previous pie chart, the most important case is 79.9% of the patients who did not attend the appointments had no health issues. Then, 10.9% of them had hypertension only and 4.9% had both hypertension anf diabetes. The other cases had a smaller impact on those who missed their appointments.

Conclusions¶

This study includes data from 110526 appointments scheduled between 2015-11-10 and 2016-8-6 for the patients in Brazil. In this section,the data Analysis explored in the previous section are discussed.

Overall, the number of the appointments that has been met by patients is higher than the missed ones; that is around 80% of the patients showed up whereas 20% of them missed their appointments. 22319 appointments scheduled in less then 7 months were missed. Therefore, it is vital to figure out the reasons behind these numbers. To do so, this project analysed how several factors help in predicting if patients will show up for their scheduled appointment. The factors examined are 'Gender', 'Age', 'Neighbourhood', 'Scholarship', 'SMS_Received', 'Hypertension', 'Diabetes', 'Alcoholism' and time difference between scheduled day and appointment day.

Gender: Firstly, the gender statistics of patients participated are approximately 65% female and 35% male. The bar graph shows that the number of female patients showed up or missed is almost double the number of the corrosponding male patients; probably due to the higher percentage of females in the sample size. Both male and female appointments have the similar rates of missed appointments, which is almost 20% of the corresponding total appointments. This leads to the result that gender does not have a clear correlation to the patient decision whether to show up for an appointment or not.

Age: Secondly, age factor was considered. Generally, the age range is (0 - 115) years old with mean age of 37 years old. 75% of the appointments were assigned to less than 55 years old patients. Moreover, the histogram shows a right skewed shape in which most of the appiontments fall to the left side of the graph; that is between 0 and 60 years old. Now, let's see the cases classified based on the No_Show decisions. The histograms of the samples who showed up and missed are both right skewed with properties similar to the overall ages histogram, and their boxplots also show that around 75% of data are for those who are less than 55 years old. Therefore, gender factor does not show an obvious help to predict patients decision.

Neighbourhood: Neighbourhood was also explored; the bar charts show that Jardim Cumburi has the highest showed up appointments (around 6252) as well as the highest missed appointments (around 1465); that is the missed is 20% of the total appointments from the city. To generalise, for every city the number of attended appointments is higher than the number of the missed except for the cities with very low number of scheduled appointments. There isn't a correlation from this set of data. However, I believe, there are some limitations; we need extra parameters to improve the quality of this finding, for example, the distance of the neighbourhood from the hospital.

Scholarship & SMS_Received: If we consider the scholarship parameter regardless of receiving an sms, 9.8% of all patients have the scholarship; 7.5% of them showed up. This indicates that having Bolsa Familia may encourage appointments attendance. However, not having the scholarship still leads to a higher percentage of patients who show-up which also encourage appointments attendance. Bolsa Familia is national Brazilian scholarship to help poor families who have monthly income < $140. It would be effective if information about the monthly income is also available to have a deep understanding and reasoning to this part. If we consider the SMS_Received parameter regardless of scholarship, 32.1% of all patients got an SMS; 22.3% of them showed up. This is a large number compared to those who missed in the same category, so, the SMS may encourage appointments attendance. However, without the SMS, we still have higher number of patients attending.

Now, by looking at Scholarship and SMS_Received together, it's surprising that with no Bolsa Familia nor an SMS received, more than 50% of the patients showed up the appointments compared to the 10% who missed them. When an SMS had been sent to those who have no scholarship, 21% was encouraged to attend and 7.8% did not attend. In this case, SMS only helped to slightly decrease the number of missed appointments. on the other hand, with scholarship and no SMS received, 7.8% came to the appointments and 1.3% missed them. And, the patients showed up with both the scholarship and SMS decreased to 2.1% and the missed to 1.1%. This implies that not having the scholarship nor receiving the SMS will guarantee a better performance of patients attendance.

Health Issues: Hypertension, Diabetes and Alcoholism are all possible issues that affect appointments attendance. From the sample given, hypertension is the most popular among patients although it is not the main reason for patients decision. The highest number of patients who either showed up or missed their appointments have none of the three health issues. After that comes hypertension as the second highest cause for either decisions and then hypertension and diabetes together. Almost 2% of those who showed up or missed their appointments suffer from Alcoholism.

Time Difference between Scheduled Day and Appointment Day: In the last question, the time difference between scheduled day and appointment day was analysed (I will call it time difference in this context). Regardless of patients decision, the histogram of time difference has a positively skewed shape at which most of the sample size is concentrated to the left side, which shows that 75% of appointments were less than 14 days away from their scheduled day. Showed-up and missed appointments time difference histograms are also positively skewed. 75% of time difference is less than 11 days for showed-up Appointments whereas a higher value of 22 days for missed appointments. Therefore, there is a large probability that patients will attend their appointments if the time difference between scheduled day and appointment day is lower than 11 days.

All in all, the most effective factor to help in predict if the patient will commit to the appointments is 'Time Difference between Scheduled Day and Appointment Day'.
